Total / 65 / 50 / 41 354 / 662 / 1601
In the first 5 months of the year, 368 people were admitted to hospital
with measles (provisional data as of 5 June 2002). Of these, 63 had
pulmonary complications, 13 had encephalitis, and 3 died. The 3 deaths were
of children aged 6 months, 4 years, and 10 years. Most of the admissions
(258/368) were to Cotugno hospital in Naples; in this hospital the age of
patients with measles ranged from 15 days to 68 years, with 83 per cent of
the admissions of children under 15 years of age.
Conclusions
-----------
The epidemic in Campania has the characteristics of an epidemic in a
population with intermediate levels of vaccine coverage - levels are high
enough to increase the length of interepidemic period (In Campania, the
last epidemic occurred in 1996, and the interepidemic period was much
longer than that observed in the absence of vaccination: 6 years versus 3
years), but too low to interrupt transmission of the infection.
The key to preventing epidemics of this type is to address the accumulation
of susceptibles in all age groups as quickly as possible. The regional
health authorities have thus recommended: a) intensification of active
vaccination of those exposed in family and school settings; b) vaccination
starting at 6 months of age, with subsequent revaccination after 1 year of
those children vaccinated between 6 and 12 months. This measure was
introduced to protect infants under 12 months of age during the epidemic,
since cases were observed in this age group; c) offering vaccine to all
people who have not been vaccinated or who have no history of measles.
According to SPES results, incidence in the 20 other regions of Italy was
much lower than that observed in Campania; in fact, excluding this region,
the incidence of measles between January and May 2002 averaged 77 cases/100
000. Nevertheless, apart from Campania, there are other areas with low
measles vaccination coverage. To prevent new epidemics it is therefore
essential to have a strong political and technical commitment that
guarantees high levels of coverage in all the regions, both in children
aged 12 to 24 months and in older children. There is a need for national
and regional health authorities to agree a strategic plan for measles
elimination. In addition to measures aimed at strengthening the routine
vaccination program (for example, reducing missed opportunities and
inappropriate contraindications, and training health staff to improve the
management of immunization services), the implementation of a vaccination
campaign targeting all children between 5 and 13 years of age, regardless
of their previous vaccine and disease history, should be considered. By
vaccinating susceptible individuals in the age group with the highest risk,
and administering a second dose to those already vaccinated, this campaign
may interrupt measles transmission.
